\begin_layout Section
Safety margins in winch launching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three safety margins that could apply to all phases of winch launching
 .
 To give them similar form, we write them in terms of load factors (gas).
 First a 
\emph on
structural
\emph default
 safety margin which shows how many g's of wing loading we are from breaking
 the wing.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{sm}_{struct}=\frac{L_{max.design}-L(t)}{W}=n_{1}\left(1-\frac{m_{w}y_{G}}{my_{L}}\right)-\frac{L(t)}{W}\label{eq: structural SM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next the stall safety margin shows how many g's of wing loading we are away
 from stalling the wing at a certain speed.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{sm}_{stall}=\frac{L_{max}(v)-L(t)}{W}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{max}(v)=\frac{1}{2}\rho SC_{L.max}v^{2}$
\end_inset

, the maximum lift that can be generated at speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 This occurs when the wing coefficient reaches its maximum (at the maximum
 angle of attack).
 In our discussion we will use 
\bar under
only one stall speed
\bar default
, the unaccelerated stall speed 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{S}$
\end_inset

 .
 Any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accelerated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stall effects are in the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $L(t)$
\end_inset

 vs a maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $L.$
\end_inset

 We can write rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{sm}_{stall}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the unaccelerated stall speed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{sm}_{stall}=\left(\frac{v}{V_{S}}\right)^{2}-\frac{L(t)}{W}\label{eq:SM stall}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Third, the rope break margin which shows how close the rope is to breaking
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{sm}_{rope}=\frac{T_{wl}-T(t)}{W}\label{eq: tension SM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{wl}$
\end_inset

is the weak link breaking force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rope break recovery safety margin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last safety margin applies during the rotation and initial climb, and
 is more difficult to write.
 The margin is to have more than sufficient speed and height after a rope
 break or power failure to recover to level flight.
 Browning
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Browning2007SafetyBGA"

\end_inset

, Hills
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hills2007SafetyBGA"

\end_inset

 and Moore
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "2011MooreRecoveryASK21"

\end_inset

 did simulations to find safe speeds and heights, and heights lost during
 recovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to define a safety margin in closed form that we can apply at each
 time during the climb without doing an additional simulation, so we solve
 the differential equations approximately for a zero-g pushover and recovery
 dive.
 At the time of the break, the glider has speed 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{br}$
\end_inset

 and climb angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{br},$
\end_inset

and the horizontal velocity is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\approx V_{br}cos\gamma_{br}$
\end_inset

, and the vertical velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{y}\approx V_{br}sin\gamma_{br}$
\end_inset

 The pilot puts the glider in a ballistic (zero lift) pushover right after
 a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{delay}$
\end_inset

 after the rope break.
 By then the glider has slowed to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ball}=\sqrt{V_{x}^{2}+(V_{y}-gt_{delay})^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and has risen a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y_{0}=V_{y}t_{delay}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume the pilot maintains the same glider attitude, and the horizontal
 stabilizer keeps the glider very close to the initial climb angle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the ballistic pushover the horizontal speed is approximately conserved,
 so at the peak the speed is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}\approx V_{br}cos\gamma_{br}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Recovery without dive: 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}>V_{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the initial horizontal speed is greater than the safe recovery speed
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}$
\end_inset

, then the recovery is over, and the safety margin is the height gained
 in the ballistic arc to the peak, plus height gained by slowing to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}$
\end_inset

 which is
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sqrt{V_{x}^{2}-V_{R}^{2}}}{2g}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The height gain during the ballistic pushover is obtained by energy conservation
; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta y_{1}\approx\frac{V_{ball}^{2}-V_{r}^{2}}{2g}=\frac{V_{r}^{2}}{2g}\left(\left(\frac{V_{ball}}{V_{r}}\right)^{2}-1\right)\label{eq:height change in ballistic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the recovery safety margin 
\emph on
expressed in height
\emph default
 
\emph on
above the ground
\emph default
 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{sm}_{recov}=y_{br}+V_{y}t_{delay}+\frac{V_{r}^{2}}{2g}\left(\left(\frac{V_{ball}}{V_{r}}\right)^{2}-1\right)+\frac{\sqrt{V_{x}^{2}-V_{R}^{2}}}{2g}\label{eq: recovery SM without dive}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

, and this always positive.
 We could subtract a small drag term, but the drag will be much less than
 seen in normal flight because no lift is being generated during the zero-g
 push over, and the average speed is much less than in normal flight, so
 we can neglect it in this case of recovery without dive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Recovery with dive: 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{x}<V_{r}$
\end_inset

 constant transverse acceleration 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case where a dive is needed before level flight, the ballistic arc
 continues until the glider has reached speed 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}$
\end_inset

 (a slower speed could be chosen, but we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}$
\end_inset

 for simplicity and to be conservative).
 Then the pilot must pull out to level flight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the beginning of the dive the angle is below the horizon at
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{d}=tan^{-1}\left(\frac{v_{y}}{V_{x}}\right)=tan^{-1}\left(\frac{\sqrt{V_{r}^{2}-V_{x}^{2}}}{V_{x}}\right)\label{eq: gamma dive}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Appendix (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: Recovery height change"

\end_inset

) we show that when a dive is necessary the safety margin is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{sm}_{recov}=y_{br}+V_{y}t_{delay}+\frac{V_{r}^{2}}{2g}\left[\left(\frac{V_{ball}}{V_{r}}\right)^{2}-(1+2\Gamma+2\Gamma^{2})\right]\label{eq: recovery SM with dive-2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

, where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma=\frac{\gamma_{d}^{p}sin\frac{\gamma_{d}^{p}}{2}}{n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}^{p}sin\frac{\gamma_{d}^{p}}{2}}\label{eq: big Gamma-1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See the Appendix (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: Recovery height change"

\end_inset

) fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: approx vs GSM recovery height change"

\end_inset

 that shows this method is validated by full simulations of the recovery
 dive if 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.53.$
\end_inset

 Also in the best fit to the simulation we find 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{r}=1.5V_{S},$
\end_inset

 the same conservative but realistic speed Moore proposed for the recovery
 speed (beginning of the dive), which is typically about the best-glide
 speed, which may not be surprising because this corresponds to the angle
 of attack Moore chose.
 The best fit to Moore's data also gives 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{p}=1.5,$
\end_inset

 Browning's
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Browning2007SafetyBGA"

\end_inset

 value chosen for the pullout constant g's.
\end_layout

