\begin_layout Subsubsection
Wing bending under inertial loads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the moment we ignore gravity, the pilot, the fuselage and the tail.
 We just consider a flying wing under 
\emph on
turning
\emph default
 acceleration (maneuvering).
 The lift it generates is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{1}=m_{w}a
\]

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{w}$
\end_inset

is the mass of the wing.
 If the mass in the wing (mass per length) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{w}(y)$
\end_inset

 were distributed in exactly the same manner (or function) as lift is distribute
d (lift per length 
\begin_inset Formula $l(y)$
\end_inset

 along the half-span 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

/2, then the wing would generate the lift without bending because each wing
 segment generates exactly the lift needed to turn that segment's mass in
 the circle.
 But because the mass is not distributed in the same manner as the lift,
 it will create bending along the wing which could be positive or negative.
 We study only the bending of the wing spar at the center of the span:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\int_{0}^{b/2}(l_{1}(y)-\mu_{w}(y)a)ydy
\]

\end_inset

Let's define normalized functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{M}$
\end_inset

 that describe how the wing's lift and mass are distributed (each function
 has integral of 1): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=\int_{0}^{b/2}\left(L_{1}f_{L}(y)-m_{w}af_{m}(y)\right)ydy
\]

\end_inset

But 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}=m_{w}a$
\end_inset

, so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=L_{1}\int_{0}^{b/2}\left(f_{L}(y)-f_{m}(y)\right)ydy
\]

\end_inset

The integrals above are simply the definitions of the center of lift 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}$
\end_inset

 and center of gravity 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{G}$
\end_inset

 of the wing measured from the glider center.
 So 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=L_{1}(y_{L}-y_{G})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we add the mass of everything else: fuselage, tail, pilot,etc which
 is non-lifing mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{nl}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the wing must generate an additional lift to turn these masses: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{2}=m_{nl}a=\frac{m_{nl}}{m_{w}}L_{1}
\]

\end_inset

This lift will create a relatively 
\bar under
large
\bar default
 bending moment because the mass is larger and there is no cancellation
 of a negative term..
 If the bending is not huge, we can assume that the lift distribution function
 only changes magnitude as the load increases
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{2}=L_{2}y_{L}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total bending moment is .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}+M_{2}=L_{2}\left(\left[1+\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}\right]y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}y_{G}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's we write the total lift in terms of a load factor: 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}+L_{2}=n_{a}mg$
\end_inset

 , the maximum safe load .
 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}+L_{2}=L_{2}\left[1+\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}\right]=n_{a}mg$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}=n_{a}mg/\left(1+\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}\right)$
\end_inset

, so 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{iner}=n_{a}mg\left(y_{L}-\frac{\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}y_{G}}{1+\frac{m_{w}}{m_{nl}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{iner}=n_{a}W\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{iner}=n_{a}Wy_{L}-n_{a}m_{w}gy_{G}\label{eq: inertial load bending-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

, because the glider mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m=m_{w}+m_{nl},$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $W=mg$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Wing bending under non-inertial loads at top of winch launch
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Wing-bending- top of launch"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For now, we will consider the case just before release.
 The glider is essentially just above the winch and the rope angle is greater
 than 70 deg above the horizon.
 This is the part of the launch when the tension 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is acting most directly against the lift and when the wings must generate
 the most lift per unit of tension.
 So the difference in the wing bending vs an inertial load will be the largest
 here.
 We ignore the difference between 70 degrees and vertical: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L-mg-T=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here there is no acceleration, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=F_{ni}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ni}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the non-inertial loads, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ni}=mg+T$
\end_inset

.
 So there is an upward bending of the wings due to lift generation, and
 a downward bending due to the weight of the wings: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{st}=F_{ni}gy_{L}-m_{w}gy_{G}\label{eq:Static bending first}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write the non-inertial forces in terms of a load factor: 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ni}=n_{ni}mg$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{st}=n_{ni}Wy_{L}-m_{w}gy_{G}\label{eq:static load bending}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference in wing bending between the inertial load case eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: inertial load bending-1"

\end_inset

 vs the non-inertial load case eqn 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:static load bending}$
\end_inset

 is that the load factor 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is in both terms in the inertial case, but only in the first term in the
 non-inertial one.
 So for equal loads, the non-inertial case bends the wing 
\begin_inset Formula $more$
\end_inset

 than for inertial loads.
 This is because of the mass of the wing: in the inertial case, the lift
 bending is partially opposed by the opposite bending needed to accelerate
 the mass distributed along the wing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maximum bending moment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the glider load was certified as purely inertial, from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: inertial load bending-1"

\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{max}=n_{1}W\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)\label{eq: Max bending moment}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the glider load was certified as inertial in addition to the glider's
 weight then we would subtract a term , from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: inertial load bending-1"

\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{max}=(n_{1}-1)W\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)+Wy_{L}-m_{w}gy_{G}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{max}=n_{1}W\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)-m_{w}gy_{G}\label{eq: Max bending with weight static}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These differ only in the last (small) term 
\begin_inset Formula $-m_{w}gy_{G},$
\end_inset

 so we're on the safe side if we take the smaller of the two (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Max bending with weight static"

\end_inset

) in any case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Winch maneuvering speed: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the winch launch the case with the greatest ratio of non-inertial to
 inertial loading is at the top of the launch, as treated in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Wing-bending- top of launch"

\end_inset

, so it the configuration that determines the maximum speed to fly on the
 winch.
 This will be the speed where bending moment at the top of the winch launch
 will equal the maximum bending moment at the maximum inertial load.
 The lift terms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Static bending first"

\end_inset

, and using 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ni}=L$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{ni}=Lgy_{L}-m_{w}gy_{G}=M_{max}=n_{1}W\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)-m_{w}gy_{G}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\rho SC_{L.max}V_{Aw}^{2}gy_{L}-m_{w}gy_{G}=\frac{1}{2}\rho SC_{L.max}V_{A}^{2}\left(y_{L}-\frac{m_{w}}{m}y_{G}\right)-m_{w}gy_{G}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we take for our proposed winch maneuvering speed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{Aw}=V_{A}\sqrt{1-\frac{m_{w}y_{G}}{my_{L}}}\label{eq: VAw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Appendix: Height change during dive
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: Recovery height change"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the beginning of the dive the angle is below the horizon at (reproducing
 eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: gamma dive"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{d}=tan^{-1}\left(\frac{v_{y}}{V_{x}}\right)=tan^{-1}\left(\frac{\sqrt{V_{r}^{2}-V_{x}^{2}}}{V_{x}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The differential equations can be written in terms of speed and the climb
 angle, from Newton's laws written for directions along the path and perpendicul
ar to it.
 We neglect drag for now.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\dot{v}=mgsin\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ma_{\bot}=mv\dot{\gamma}=L-mgcos\gamma
\]

\end_inset

If the pilot executes a pullout with 
\emph on
constant turning g's
\emph default
 (constant turning acceleration) as suggested by Browning
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Browning2007SafetyBGA"

\end_inset

, rather than constant lift, then 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 changes such that 
\begin_inset Formula $L-mgcos\gamma=n_{p}mg$
\end_inset

 , a constant.
 This choice of maneuver has the advantage that the pilot feels the turning
 acceleration directly as an additional seat force and can keep that roughly
 constant.
 It is similar to the constant angle of attack pullout modeled by Moore
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "2011MooreRecoveryASK21"

\end_inset

, because in a constant AoA pullout more lift is generated as v increases
 toward the bottom of the pullout, where it is needed.
 So this keeps the glider away from stall danger.
 In terms of symbols: 
\begin_inset Formula $L=n_{p}mg+mgcos\gamma$
\end_inset

, which increases toward the bottom of the dive (low 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 The rotation rate slows as v increases in the dive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{p}$
\end_inset

 the dive angle changes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{d}$
\end_inset

 to zero, and the average flight angle is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\gamma}=\frac{\gamma_{d}}{2}$
\end_inset

 below the horizon (a bar over a variable means average).
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{p}\approx\frac{\gamma_{d}}{\bar{\dot{\gamma}}}\approx\approx\frac{\gamma_{d}m\bar{v}}{n_{p}mg}=\frac{\gamma_{d}\bar{v}}{n_{p}g}\label{eq: pullup time-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The height lost will be approximately
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta y_{2}\approx\bar{v_{y}}t_{p}=\bar{v}sin\bar{\gamma}t_{p}\label{eq: height lost 1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we estimate the average speed during the pull-up.
 The final speed (after the pullout) is from the average acceleration along
 the path: 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{f}\approx V_{r}+gsin\bar{\gamma}\,t_{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming a linear speed increase during the pullout 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{v}\approx V_{r}+\frac{1}{2}g\left(sin\bar{\gamma}\right)\,t_{p}\label{eq:avg speed 1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.We substitute this into eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pullup time-1"

\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{p}:$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{p}=\frac{\gamma_{d}V_{r}}{g\left[n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma}\right]}\label{eq: pull up time finished-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and the average speed during the pull up is using eqns 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:avg speed 1-1"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: pull up time finished-1"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{v}\approx V_{r}\left(1+\frac{\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma}}{n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the height lost, using the previous equation and eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: height lost 1-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta y_{2}\approx\bar{v}sin\bar{\gamma}t_{p}\label{eq: height lost finished-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta y_{2}\approx\frac{V_{r}^{2}}{g}\left(1+\frac{\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma}}{(n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma})}\right)sin\bar{\gamma}\frac{\gamma_{1}}{(n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We add 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y_{1}$
\end_inset

(eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:height change in ballistic"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y_{2}$
\end_inset

to get the total height change for the entire recovery after rope break:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta y=\frac{V_{r}^{2}}{2g}\left[\left(\frac{V_{ball}}{Vr}\right)^{2}-(1+2\Gamma'+2\Gamma'^{2})\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma'=\frac{\gamma_{d}sin\frac{\gamma_{d}}{2}}{n_{p}-\frac{1}{2}\gamma_{d}sin\bar{\gamma}}\label{eq: big Gamma-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


